01:15:42.800 --> 01:15:46.630
importantly, making them express CCR7, that

1261
01:15:46.680 --> 01:15:50.600
makes them migrate to lymph nodes where they can start a systemic

1262
01:15:50.660 --> 01:15:51.820
immune response.

1263
01:15:52.720 --> 01:15:56.200
At the same time, 4-1BB ligand can also act

1264
01:15:56.280 --> 01:16:00.000
locally directly on T cells in the tumor microenvironment

1265
01:16:00.380 --> 01:16:04.340
to promote their expansion and also memory formation.

1266
01:16:06.520 --> 01:16:10.320
But CD40 receptor is present on many different

1267
01:16:10.460 --> 01:16:14.340
cell types in the tumor microenvironment, and these

1268
01:16:14.400 --> 01:16:17.520
cells can also react to CD40 ligand stimuli.

1269
01:16:18.160 --> 01:16:22.100
For example, we see upregulation of receptors for T cell

1270
01:16:22.140 --> 01:16:25.360
transmigration from blood vessel into the tumor

1271
01:16:25.460 --> 01:16:28.920
microenvironment. We can see an M2 to M1

1272
01:16:29.540 --> 01:16:32.700
differentiation of macrophages and also a

1273
01:16:32.720 --> 01:16:36.520
downregulation of different tumor-promoting

1274
01:16:36.620 --> 01:16:40.520
factors such as TGF-beta, collagen, and fibroblast

1275
01:16:40.640 --> 01:16:41.520
growth factor.

1276
01:16:43.200 --> 01:16:47.009
So we have been focusing on pancreatic cancer, and you know this is

1277
01:16:47.300 --> 01:16:50.020
a cancer with a very dismal prognosis.

1278
01:16:50.660 --> 01:16:54.260
And they are commonly treated first line with different chemotherapies

1279
01:16:54.280 --> 01:16:56.760
depending on their health status and age.

1280
01:16:58.180 --> 01:17:01.880
And it is an immunotherapy-resistant tumor with

1281
01:17:02.040 --> 01:17:05.800
low number of tumor-infiltrating T cells, but a high

1282
01:17:06.560 --> 01:17:10.040
level of myeloid cells in the tumor microenvironment.

1283
01:17:10.350 --> 01:17:13.740
And these are causing a very immunosuppressive

1284
01:17:13.980 --> 01:17:17.580
microenvironment. But given the mechanism of action of

1285
01:17:17.620 --> 01:17:21.120
LOAD-703, we thought that we might be able to do

1286
01:17:21.200 --> 01:17:22.500
something about

1287
01:17:23.620 --> 01:17:26.190
the tumor milieu in these patients.

1288
01:17:26.710 --> 01:17:30.400
So we have been focusing on patients that receive gemcitabine

1289
01:17:30.460 --> 01:17:31.980
and nab-paclitaxel,

1290
01:17:32.960 --> 01:17:36.540
given first line, second line, or at any line as long as they can

1291
01:17:36.740 --> 01:17:38.780
get these two chemotherapies.

1292
01:17:40.160 --> 01:17:43.840
We have some previous experience with LOAD-703 in

1293
01:17:44.160 --> 01:17:48.150
different clinical trials. It has been evaluated in melanoma, for

1294
01:17:48.240 --> 01:17:52.160
example, together with checkpoints and in different

1295
01:17:52.180 --> 01:17:55.920
pancreatic cancer studies and a few patients with different

1296
01:17:56.020 --> 01:17:57.260
solid tumors.

1297
01:17:58.220 --> 01:18:02.200
And the study I will present today is LUCON-001,

1298
01:18:02.720 --> 01:18:06.510
and it's actually a two-armed study, and it's the second arm we will

1299
01:18:06.560 --> 01:18:10.520
focus on, but I will give you a brief introduction to arm

1300
01:18:10.560 --> 01:18:14.360
one as well. So we enroll patients

1301
01:18:14.400 --> 01:18:18.080
with advanced pancreatic cancer, and they receive LOAD-703

1302
01:18:18.180 --> 01:18:20.960
together with gemcitabine and nab-paclitaxel.

1303
01:18:22.340 --> 01:18:26.060
The LOAD-703 dose was escalated in three different

1304
01:18:26.120 --> 01:18:29.320
dose levels against a fixed dose of chemotherapy.

1305
01:18:30.320 --> 01:18:33.400
We enrolled 18 patients in arm one.

1306
01:18:34.360 --> 01:18:37.800
Fifteen of them had stage four disease, and half of the

1307
01:18:37.880 --> 01:18:39.480
patients were first line.

1308
01:18:41.060 --> 01:18:44.620
The overall response rate across dose levels was

1309
01:18:44.660 --> 01:18:47.140
44% in this arm,

1310
01:18:48.380 --> 01:18:52.340
and the overall survival was 9.3 months in this rather

1311
01:18:52.420 --> 01:18:54.860
heterogeneous group of patients.

1312
01:18:56.440 --> 01:19:00.400
In this study, we also confirmed that we had activation

1313
01:19:00.500 --> 01:19:04.080
of CD8 positive T cells, and it was especially the

1314
01:19:04.120 --> 01:19:07.420
effector memory population that was increased in blood,

1315
01:19:08.000 --> 01:19:11.280
and these cells could react to a number of different

1316
01:19:11.360 --> 01:19:12.700
tumor-associated

1317
01:19:12.820 --> 01:19:16.768
antigens.In tumors, we can see

1318
01:19:16.848 --> 01:19:20.768
a massive upregulation of different immune biomarkers that

1319
01:19:20.828 --> 01:19:24.648
are related to a T cell response. And in this string

1320
01:19:24.658 --> 01:19:28.448
analysis, we can also see that it's a CD40-dependent

1321
01:19:28.488 --> 01:19:32.447
TH1 immune activation that seems to be ongoing.

1322
01:19:34.288 --> 01:19:38.248
So coming now to LuCON 001 arm two. Now,

1323
01:19:38.308 --> 01:19:42.268
when we know that we have expanded T cells in these patients,

1324
01:19:42.408 --> 01:19:45.808
we thought, what if we add atezolizumab, which is an

1325
01:19:45.928 --> 01:19:49.008
anti-PD-L1 antibody, to this combination?

1326
01:19:50.168 --> 01:19:53.948
And in this study, LOAD 703 is given every other

1327
01:19:54.068 --> 01:19:56.988
week, as you can see below, and

1328
01:19:57.408 --> 01:20:00.988
chemotherapy is given the usual day one,

1329
01:20:01.448 --> 01:20:04.167
eight, and 15 in a 28-day cycle.

1330
01:20:04.648 --> 01:20:08.528
Atezolizumab was given the first day of each

1331
01:20:08.548 --> 01:20:11.168
chemotherapy cycle, so every fourth week.

1332
01:20:13.268 --> 01:20:17.108
Also here, patients with advanced pancreatic cancer at

1333
01:20:17.168 --> 01:20:20.488
any line of treatment were enrolled, as long as they were

1334
01:20:20.528 --> 01:20:23.908
eligible for gemcitabine and nab-paclitaxel.

1335
01:20:23.928 --> 01:20:27.788
We took the two highest dose levels to test in this triplet

1336
01:20:27.888 --> 01:20:31.748
combination and enrolled 24 patients, 12

1337
01:20:31.788 --> 01:20:35.668
patients per dose level. Twenty-two of the patients had

1338
01:20:35.808 --> 01:20:39.388
stage four disease, and 13 were treated first

1339
01:20:39.488 --> 01:20:39.868
line.

1340
01:20:41.548 --> 01:20:45.308
So of course, these patients had all the different adverse

1341
01:20:45.368 --> 01:20:47.618
events that are related to chemotherapy.

1342
01:20:48.088 --> 01:20:50.148
But considering LOAD 703,

1343
01:20:51.128 --> 01:20:54.908
this didn't add so much to the patients other than fever,

1344
01:20:55.008 --> 01:20:58.908
chills, fatigues, which is kind of expected if you inject

1345
01:20:59.248 --> 01:21:00.908
a virus into the body.

1346
01:21:01.908 --> 01:21:05.828
We did see some kidney-related toxicity that

1347
01:21:05.908 --> 01:21:09.748
was possibly attributed to our virus, but

1348
01:21:09.848 --> 01:21:13.288
also to atezolizumab or even chemotherapy.

1349
01:21:16.428 --> 01:21:20.188
In this patient, again, we could see the massive upregulation

1350
01:21:20.368 --> 01:21:22.988
of adaptive response biomarkers.

1351
01:21:23.948 --> 01:21:27.628
And in particular, it was markers related to T

1352
01:21:27.688 --> 01:21:31.108
cell activation. But we could also see some

1353
01:21:31.188 --> 01:21:34.768
biomarkers that were decreased in these patients after treatment

1354
01:21:34.848 --> 01:21:38.768
initiation, and those were biomarkers of fibroblast

1355
01:21:38.908 --> 01:21:41.407
proliferation and acute inflammation.

1356
01:21:43.188 --> 01:21:47.068
We could confirm that we had CD8 positive effector

1357
01:21:47.128 --> 01:21:49.388
memory T cells that increased in blood

1358
01:21:50.528 --> 01:21:53.188
and T regulatory cells that were

1359
01:21:53.368 --> 01:21:56.068
downregulated in these patients.

1360
01:21:57.688 --> 01:22:01.508
So the overall response rate in arm two was

1361
01:22:01.768 --> 01:22:05.388
38% across dose levels, but we did

1362
01:22:05.398 --> 01:22:09.268
see three complete responses in these patients.

1363
01:22:10.568 --> 01:22:14.248
All of the patients that had complete responses had stage

1364
01:22:14.348 --> 01:22:17.248
four disease, so with liver metastasis.

1365
01:22:17.868 --> 01:22:21.808
All three had prior surgery with either gemcitabine

1366
01:22:21.848 --> 01:22:25.628
and nab-paclitaxel or folfirinox as neoadjuvant or

1367
01:22:25.768 --> 01:22:29.528
both neoadjuvant and adjuvant, plus or minus

1368
01:22:29.588 --> 01:22:30.608
radiotherapy.

1369
01:22:32.268 --> 01:22:36.248
They were quite durable. The first patient in complete response

1370
01:22:36.828 --> 01:22:40.708
was in complete response for over two years, the second one

1371
01:22:40.748 --> 01:22:44.588
and a half year, and the third, unfortunately, only a couple of

1372
01:22:44.728 --> 01:22:45.188
months.

1373
01:22:47.318 --> 01:22:50.988
The progression-free survival was seven months, and

1374
01:22:51.168 --> 01:22:55.028
overall survival 9.9 months. But

1375
01:22:55.128 --> 01:22:58.548
if we look then at the patients that were treated

1376
01:22:58.728 --> 01:22:59.688
first line,

1377
01:23:00.588 --> 01:23:03.468
we could see that the median overall survival was

1378
01:23:03.588 --> 01:23:07.188
14.7 months with a one-year survival of

1379
01:23:07.508 --> 01:23:10.988
62%. The two-year survival was

1380
01:23:11.228 --> 01:23:15.048
31%, and the PFS 11.1

1381
01:23:15.108 --> 01:23:18.928
months. Overall response rate, 54%.

1382
01:23:19.368 --> 01:23:22.858
And all of the patients that had a complete response were treated

1383
01:23:23.028 --> 01:23:25.688
first line. And of course, the first line

1384
01:23:25.728 --> 01:23:29.228
treated patients are not many. This is a small

1385
01:23:29.368 --> 01:23:33.048
population of 13 patients, so that's something to keep in

1386
01:23:33.128 --> 01:23:36.838
mind comparing this data to what we know from

1387
01:23:36.868 --> 01:23:37.737
chemotherapy.

1388
01:23:38.648 --> 01:23:42.528
But nevertheless, if we compare the survival of

1389
01:23:42.548 --> 01:23:46.448
arm one and arm two in this study, it surely looks like

1390
01:23:46.668 --> 01:23:49.588
atezolizumab is providing some

1391
01:23:50.888 --> 01:23:54.427
survival benefit to these patients.

1392
01:23:54.528 --> 01:23:57.828
But is it LOAD 703, the antibody, or both?

1393
01:23:58.308 --> 01:24:01.788
Obviously, we don't know that yet, and the next step is to

1394
01:24:01.828 --> 01:24:05.548
perform a randomized four-armed trial

1395
01:24:05.928 --> 01:24:09.888
to evaluate the contribution of each component.

1396
01:24:09.918 --> 01:24:13.288
And considering that all in all, we have treated now

1397
01:24:13.358 --> 01:24:16.848
74 patients with pancreatic cancer in different

1398
01:24:16.928 --> 01:24:20.868
trials, the next step will be also a registration

1399
01:24:20.968 --> 01:24:24.848
trial. So we have discussed with the FDA the design already.

1400
01:24:26.128 --> 01:24:30.008
So with that cliffhanger, who is responsible for

1401
01:24:30.068 --> 01:24:33.688
the effect we see, I will leave you to acknowledge

1402
01:24:34.088 --> 01:24:37.948
the patients and families and also the PI in this study,

1403
01:24:38.088 --> 01:24:41.848
Benjamin Mascher at Baylor College of Medicine, and also

1404
01:24:41.908 --> 01:24:45.368
Malcolm Brenner, who is the scientific advisor to this

1405
01:24:45.768 --> 01:24:49.568
project. Of course, there's a lot of people involved when you are doing a

1406
01:24:49.608 --> 01:24:53.588
trial, and this arm one, two study actually took

1407
01:24:53.628 --> 01:24:57.168
10 years. So I'm glad to be here today and

1408
01:24:57.268 --> 01:25:01.048
present it finally. So with that, I'm happy to take any

1409
01:25:01.088 --> 01:25:01.828
questions.

1410
01:25:02.668 --> 01:25:03.028
Thank you.

1411
01:25:07.668 --> 01:25:11.508
Excellent. Congratulations on a really titanic effort in pancreatic cancer, a very

1412
01:25:11.548 --> 01:25:12.288
hard disease.

1413
01:25:13.728 --> 01:25:17.448
It's notable that you saw really better responses in the

1414
01:25:17.508 --> 01:25:20.348
earlier line patients, and it makes me wonder about the role

1415
01:25:21.128 --> 01:25:24.916
ofOf this agent in neoadjuvant therapy for inoperable locally advanced

1416
01:25:24.976 --> 01:25:28.436
disease, is this an opportunity to convert patients to

1417
01:25:28.456 --> 01:25:31.146
resectable from truly unresectable? Are you investigating that?

1418
01:25:32.276 --> 01:25:33.936
I think it is. I think

1419
01:25:34.976 --> 01:25:38.336
LOAD 703 would really have great potential even

1420
01:25:38.396 --> 01:25:41.626
earlier stages. When we were

1421
01:25:42.816 --> 01:25:46.736
talking about where to begin with this study, at least we knew that we

1422
01:25:46.836 --> 01:25:48.896
had to have pretty healthy patients.

1423
01:25:48.956 --> 01:25:52.776
It is an activating immunotherapy, and pancreatic cancer is a

1424
01:25:52.856 --> 01:25:56.696
rapid disease, unfortunately. We had to go in early,

1425
01:25:57.016 --> 01:25:59.636
but we didn't dare to go that early.

1426
01:25:59.736 --> 01:26:03.136
But I think that's a really interesting next step.

1427
01:26:03.656 --> 01:26:04.116
Yeah. It's

1428
01:26:04.916 --> 01:26:08.096
a subset of pancreatic cancer that is neither metastatic nor curable, so it's a

1429
01:26:08.116 --> 01:26:11.156
great place to think about. We have a question on the right.

1430
01:26:11.836 --> 01:26:15.736
Hi. So I might have missed it, but how long are you able to

1431
01:26:15.816 --> 01:26:19.585
detect this virus after the treatment circulating in the

1432
01:26:19.616 --> 01:26:19.856
body?

1433
01:26:20.596 --> 01:26:24.296
Yeah. So it's given intratumorally, so it

1434
01:26:24.356 --> 01:26:26.335
doesn't really spread to

1435
01:26:27.716 --> 01:26:31.496
blood that much. You can detect it in blood maybe a

1436
01:26:31.556 --> 01:26:35.196
day after, but then neutralizing antibodies will

1437
01:26:35.376 --> 01:26:38.576
remove any virus that are circulating in blood.

1438
01:26:39.296 --> 01:26:40.476
And in the tumor,

1439
01:26:41.776 --> 01:26:45.056
we actually have only biopsies two weeks later,

1440
01:26:46.096 --> 01:26:49.916
and then we see the effects of the transgenes, but we

1441
01:26:49.956 --> 01:26:52.816
don't see so much of the virus anymore.

1442
01:26:52.936 --> 01:26:56.716
So I think in the next study, we will try to take a biopsy

1443
01:26:56.796 --> 01:26:59.976
earlier just to see a little bit how long it persists.

1444
01:27:00.036 --> 01:27:03.476
Okay. And second question is, do tumor cells

1445
01:27:03.536 --> 01:27:05.896
acquire any resistance mechanisms to

1446
01:27:06.996 --> 01:27:10.416
this virus therapy, for example, like some mutations that

1447
01:27:10.476 --> 01:27:12.816
disables the replication of the viruses?

1448
01:27:13.296 --> 01:27:14.256
Yeah. Well,

1449
01:27:15.316 --> 01:27:15.336
I

1450
01:27:16.276 --> 01:27:20.056
haven't seen any resistance to the oncolytic

1451
01:27:20.156 --> 01:27:23.516
effect, at least. The virus seems to replicate well.

1452
01:27:24.436 --> 01:27:26.136
I think the only thing to

1453
01:27:27.476 --> 01:27:31.416
push back on the replication would be perhaps a chemotherapy that would

1454
01:27:31.456 --> 01:27:35.396
disrupt the tubulin system or so, and not one

1455
01:27:35.476 --> 01:27:39.456
like paclitaxel that keeps it up, and maybe like

1456
01:27:39.496 --> 01:27:43.276
vincristine that breaks it down. But in terms

1457
01:27:43.376 --> 01:27:46.616
of other mechanisms, we do see that when you

1458
01:27:46.696 --> 01:27:47.556
stimulate

1459
01:27:49.776 --> 01:27:53.716
the immune system in this way, it will, of course, upregulate PD-1

1460
01:27:53.736 --> 01:27:57.316
and PD-L1, one of the reasons we wanted to include a

1461
01:27:57.376 --> 01:28:00.196
checkpoint. But something else we see is

1462
01:28:01.296 --> 01:28:05.136
all the patients that progress rapidly, they have a lot of

1463
01:28:05.236 --> 01:28:08.956
IL-6. So that would be something I would like to

1464
01:28:08.996 --> 01:28:12.056
block because I think that's also a kind of a resistance

1465
01:28:12.116 --> 01:28:13.016
mechanism.

1466
01:28:13.356 --> 01:28:14.036
Yeah. Thank you.

1467
01:28:17.616 --> 01:28:21.116
Okay. It's very interesting. Can you try?

1468
01:28:22.616 --> 01:28:23.796
I noticed the

1469
01:28:25.076 --> 01:28:28.516
efficacy is quite well, but

1470
01:28:29.396 --> 01:28:30.336
we also

1471
01:28:31.316 --> 01:28:34.476
find the safety profile is also very good.

1472
01:28:35.116 --> 01:28:38.856
Do you think this combination have a protect function?

1473
01:28:41.256 --> 01:28:43.496
It's a very good question.

1474
01:28:45.936 --> 01:28:49.896
It is a weird thing when you give the LOAD 703 virus to

1475
01:28:49.996 --> 01:28:51.076
patients, but

1476
01:28:52.756 --> 01:28:56.596
we always get the responses from the PI, like, "The patient seems

1477
01:28:56.676 --> 01:29:00.136
to be doing so well, and they are happy." And I'm

1478
01:29:00.176 --> 01:29:03.996
starting to think that maybe the immune system also will

1479
01:29:04.056 --> 01:29:07.786
affect how you feel in a way when you have

1480
01:29:08.056 --> 01:29:11.916
an immune response ongoing. But it is actually a fact that

1481
01:29:11.976 --> 01:29:12.736
in mice,

1482
01:29:13.776 --> 01:29:17.496
if you give chemotherapy, they lose weight, but they don't

1483
01:29:17.656 --> 01:29:21.296
when we combine it with our virus. And we cannot really

1484
01:29:21.336 --> 01:29:22.476
explain that yet.

1485
01:29:24.076 --> 01:29:27.346
So is this an opportunity to combine with Folfirinox, especially when we look at--

1486
01:29:27.876 --> 01:29:31.716
We know KRAS inhibitors are here. We know diraxumrasib is

1487
01:29:31.756 --> 01:29:34.576
potent but reasonably toxic, and the combination with Folfirinox may be

1488
01:29:34.616 --> 01:29:38.076
challenging. Is this a better combo with Folfirinox?

1489
01:29:39.736 --> 01:29:43.296
I'm not sure. Folfirinox is still four

1490
01:29:43.556 --> 01:29:45.076
chemos. It might

1491
01:29:46.936 --> 01:29:49.756
inhibit the immune system a little bit too much.

1492
01:29:52.736 --> 01:29:56.716
If I were to combine with something else, I think

1493
01:29:56.776 --> 01:30:00.596
I would like to combine it with perhaps T-cell therapy.

1494
01:30:01.356 --> 01:30:02.236
But I would

1495
01:30:03.736 --> 01:30:06.936
like if we could sort of remove the chemotherapy altogether,

1496
01:30:07.756 --> 01:30:11.706
if there is a way to do that, because that would really take away

1497
01:30:11.756 --> 01:30:15.016
a lot of the side effects that we do see from the

1498
01:30:15.056 --> 01:30:18.996
chemo. So that would be interesting, and maybe it works even

1499
01:30:19.016 --> 01:30:21.516
better if you don't have the chemotherapy there.

1500
01:30:22.076 --> 01:30:25.866
But you can never do that the first time you try, but

1501
01:30:26.056 --> 01:30:27.176
perhaps in the future.

1502
01:30:27.816 --> 01:30:28.196
Yeah. Although,

1503
01:30:29.496 --> 01:30:31.336
I don't know if Folfirinox is actually that lympholytic.

1504
01:30:31.376 --> 01:30:34.996
If anything, gemcitabine, which is essentially cytarabine, may actually

1505
01:30:35.036 --> 01:30:38.576
